A Glimpse Into an HTTP Response 


HTTP Response-

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Date: Tue, 19 Apr 2011 09:23:32 GMT
Server: Microsoft-IIS/6.0
X-Powered-By: ASP.NET
Set-Cookie: tracking=tI8rk7joMx44S2Uu85nSWc
X-AspNet-Version: 2.0.50727
Cache-Control: no-cache
Pragma: no-cache
Expires: Thu, 01 Jan 1970 00:00:00 GMT
Content-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 1067
<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC “-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN” “http://
www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd”><html xmlns=”http://
www.w3.org/1999/xhtml” ><head><title>Your details</title>


The first line of every HTTP Response Contains 3 items separated by spaces
The HTTP Version being used .
The Numeric status code indicating the result of the request . 200 is the most seen status code that means the request was successful and the requested resources are being retrieved.
The textual Phrase after the numeric code tells the status of the response . OK Also means that the request is accepted and the requested resource is being retrieved


The Important or Interesting point in a Response Headers.

Server - The server header tells which Web Server Software is being used. Sometimes it tells other information also like  installed modules and server operating systems.

Set-Cookie- This header indicates the cookie which is sent to the browser from the server.
the browser submits this cookie in the very next request to the server

Pragma - This header tells the browser not to store the response in its cache.

Expires -  This header tells the date when the response context has expired so it should not be stored in cache.

The Pragma and Expires headers are used frequently when dealing with dynamic pages so that the user gets the fresh version of the content .

Content-Type- This Headers tells that what type of content is shown in the response it is generally text and html.

Content-Length - This header tells the length of the message in the body in Bytes.








